With pleasure I followed almost all the postings of this forum. It occured that this board was for me the most useful source for information about the Pulsed Propulsion.<br>
<br>
I have a question, and I hope that you will help me.<br>
On Discovery channel more than a year ago I watched a film where the JC Solem and his &quot;parachute&quot; version for harnesing the yield of nuclear explosions for space propulsion - the Medusa spaceship, were mentioned. But, nothing I could find in the Net through google-search.<br>
Could you point me some sources,or kindly give coments and explanations on this topic. Is  it more efficient than the original pusher-plate`s &quot;back-wheels` drive&quot; Orion?<br>
Isn`t it interesting that in  both schemes the polyethilen plastic could play crucial role - in Orion as propelant, in Medusa version - as material for the fireball catching canopy...? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=drcarstairs>DrCarstairs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Utterly Mad Scientist</span><br>  Posts: 193<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/10/03 10:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=323.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.angelfire.com/rant/AVitW/images/biochemical.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: JC Solem`s Medusa ?</span><hr size=1> I also saw that show. So far, I have been unable to find much on Medusa. I tend to think Orion a superior concept, but it would be nice to have more information to go on. <br>
<br>
From the only source I could find:<br>
<br>
The &quot;Medusa&quot; design is a type of nuclear pulse propulsion which shares more in common with solar sails than with conventional rockets. It was proposed in the 1990s. A Medusa spacecraft would deploy a large sail ahead of it, attached by cables, and then launch nuclear explosives forward to detonate between itself and its sail. The sail would be accelerated by the impulse, and the spacecraft would follow. <br>
<br>
Medusa performs better than the classical Orion design because its &quot;pusher plate&quot; intercepts more of the bomb's blast, because its shock-absorber stroke is much longer, and because all its major structures are in tension and hence can be quite lightweight. It also scales down better. Medusa-type ships would be capable of a specific impulse between 50,000 and 100,000 seconds.<br>
<br>
Apparently there are articals about the Medusa it in the Journal of the British Interplanitary Society issues Jan93, June94, and Nov/Dec2000. unfortunatly the BIS apparently keeps these off the net.<br>
